Author: janek26
Content:
Alright, here we go:
Today we release our open source StarkNet wallet browser extension as a developers preview! üéâ üî• 

https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-x

Chrome Web Store review is still pending, and we'll add an easy way to install the extension as soon as it gets approved, but you can start buidl today! It uses the known Provider and Signer API which was first introduced by starknet.js. There's also an example DApp deployed where you can put the wallet to the test, as soon as you got it running! 

Have fun creating awesome things during the weekend, and feel free to provide feedback!

Author: .vc77
Content: Hi, I have a doubt regarding the argent-x wallet signing. According to my understanding, argent-x will deploy a contract on the user's behalf and all the requests will be going to that contract and it will redirect request to final contract address. In the case of `voting_contract`, there are functions like `init_poll`, which does not take `r` and `s` values, also there are functions like `register_voter`, which takes `r` and `s` values. From a front end perspective, how do we send requests to call these 2 functions? Do we need to pass `r` and `s` values from the js file (for 'register_voter' function) or will argent-x takes care of it?

Author: ironsoul#6439
Content: Adding to this question, we saw that Argent X passes r, s signatures to `execute` function of the contract. That's why we wonder whether we need to do something around signatures from our side?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
I'm not completely sure what you are trying to achieve. Do you have a link to a contract I could look at? 

But it is true that Argent X deploys an Account Contract for the user, and every "write" action (a transaction that modifies the state of a contract) must start from the `execute`. method of that account. To be valid, the transaction must include a signature (the `r` and `s` value) from the private key authorised on that Account Contract and Argent X can generate that signature because it manages the private key for the user. The call to  `execute`. also includes the parameters of the call that must e executed by the Account Contract (the target contract, the target method and the parameters). 

When the Account Contract calls another contract, the target contract can use `get_caller_address()` to get the address of the Account and has the guarantee that it was authorised by the owner of the Account since it went through the `execute` method that included signatures.

However, Argent X will soon be able to also generate signatures on an off-chain message (coming next week). For example maybe your contract needs a signature on the string "hello world". In that case your dapp will require Argent X to sign that string, then require Argent X to send a transaction to your contract including this extra signature in the parameters of your method. You contract can then verify the signature by getting the address of the Account with `get_caller_address()` then verifying the extra signature by calling `is_valid_signature`. on the account.

Hope that helps.

Author: ironsoul#6439
Content:
I think that your last paragraph describes exactly what we need. The source code of the contract we are trying to interact with through Argent X can be found here at the end of the article: https://starkware.notion.site/starkware/StarkNet-Voting-Workshop-b61ef5f4a62d45af86892cba3158f7e6

As you can see there, some functions require `r` and `s` as arguments. Based on what you said, these values are not passed automatically by Argent X and the functionality to generate signatures for this function will come next week?

Thank you very much!

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Yes, looking at your contracts you will first need to ask Argent X to sign the `poll_id`. and `voter_public_key`. parameters, then use that signature as an argument to the call to `register_voter`. which will be sent via the `execute`. method of an Account.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
These are good questions and we will know more when fees are introduced. But 2 things to note:
- Every user will  need an Account contract on StarkNet so this is not related to Argent specifically.
- The address of an account can be created counterfactually (without having to deploy the account), and the account can be deployed at that address later. Since you always need funds to do something on chain, you can imagine a pattern where the users installs Argent X and creates an account. The wallet shows the address but the account is not yet deployed (no cost). However, to the user it doesn't matter; he has an account with an address. He can use that address to get some fund. When the user wants to use his account to do something (say buy an NFT), the wallet can bundle the creation of the wallet and the action transparently to the user.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: I'm convinced that with a good wallet UX (and that's we're good at at Argent üôÇ )all this complexity will be abstracted to users.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: You can install it from sources which is relatively easy. It will be available on the chrome store in a few days.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: The idea is to have an account interface that all Account Contracts must implement so it should be possible to use different wallets with the same account contract. Of course your wallet may not support all the features of your account.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: We probably will but it is not the case today as the proxy pattern is not yet supported on StarkNet. There is delegatecall but no fallback method.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: aha so Argent is basically trying to set the standard wallet contract interface here

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Yes, we are working on that with Open Zeppelin which provides the other account available today https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/contracts/Account.cairo

Author: guthl_starkware
Content:
> no fallback method.
What is it needed for?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Your proxy needs to have an entry point to which all calls go (a fallback method), and that entry point then delegatecalls to the implementation. So if you implementation has a method `foo()` you can call `foo()` on the proxy contract.

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: In Solidity "selectors" are just high-level Solidity constructs so one can just use assembly to accept any selector (even if Solidity doesn't support fallback). But it seems like here on StarkNet it's a network-level concept

Author: guthl_starkware
Content:
> a fallback method
Is it not something unique to Eth because of the payable functions?

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: not really because of payable I think?

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: On StarkNet, it is also a compiler byproduct

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: See my proposal for self-describing selector

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: https://community.starknet.io/

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: https://community.starknet.io/t/self-describing-selector-to-simplify-wallets-data-parsing/61/9

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: wow didn't know this exists

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: It is new

Author: xjonathanlei
Content: nice will take a look at all of them

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: We are still on opening more issues

Author: guthl_starkware
Content: I have a fascinating one about reverted txs coming your way

Author: martriay
Content: no, there's two special functions: `receive` and `fallback`. `receive` is what you're saying, the `fallback` function is the one that's called when no selector matches the call. that's how proxies work: you receive a call for a given function that the proxy does not implement, that triggers the fallback method which grabs all of the calldata and forwards it to the implementation contract

Author: martriay
Content: proxies üåà

Author: martriay
Content: so basically proxies have two building blocks: dellegatecall + fallback function

Author: martriay
Content: the former is already implemented on starknet, the latter is blocking proxy implementations

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: StarkNet as a network is still in alpha, and so is the extension. Definitely a lot of improvements coming. These are the early days...

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
You need beta access to test the L2 wallet of the Argent mobile app which is running on ZkSync. It will be open to all next week.

But you can download and install the Argent X browser extension which is running on StarkNet now.

The Argent mobile app and the Argent X browser extension are 2 separate products for now.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: We also have a high level blog post (https://www.argent.xyz/blog/argent-x-starknet/). But the best way to learn more about how the extension works is to look at the code on github https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-x

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
Np, your feedback is really useful! 

We don't believe in seed phrases at Argent as they are a single point of failure, so the future of Argent X is Social Recovery which we have pioneered on L1. Our Account Contract already supports it but we want to wait for StarkNet to stabilize before enabling it.

Author: julien.argent.xyz

Author: Tom Brand | StarkWare#1971
Content:
@Motty | Braavos @Julien | argent.xyz the new PENDING status goal is to provide faster confirmation on L2. So assuming you are catching this new status, you will be able to use those 2 apps within few minutes.
All api calls using `blockNumber=pending`, will work on the pending state and should be much faster. Currently it works on Goerli, and we will upgrade Mainnet once we see it is stable. Would love to hear your feedback if this improves the problem you are facing.

Author: janek26
Content:
Hey,

this channel is for Argent X issues/improvements **only**. 
Let us know if you have any issues using it or integrating it into the DApps you are building, or if you want to share any information around it (Argent X, DApp ecosystem or starknet.js related)

If you're looking to get test tokens, **you can mint them yourself** using the Argent X UI or our test DApp https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-x#-example-dapp
If you want to request tokens anyways, or sent some to somebody **(they are worthless, and always will be)** go to #üì∫ÔΩúcommunity-calls 

Smalltalk and gm/gn can be done in #üïóÔΩúgm-gn and the other Community channels, please keep the other channels clean for the builders, bugs and improvements, so they do not need to scroll through the whole channel to find the informations valuable to them and the product they're building

Thanks all!

Author: hubsmoke
Content: also I have a question about the Guardian system, why is this necessary / included in the account abstraction in ArgentX?

Author: janek26
Content:
it's just an implementation detail which is different from openzeppelin's account contract, so we may introduce additional (security) features in the future
the guardian is always initialized as `0` in the current version. If the guardian isnt set the implementation behaves the same way as openzeppelins contracts

As mentioned a few times you can all mint tokens yourself using the mint button in the extension.
Your wallet needs to be deployed (Not showing `Deploying...`, takes ~5mins on goerli) and the balance wont update immediately, but you need to wait for the transaction to pass (another 5 mins)
If you want to share your wallet address anyways please do so in #üì∫ÔΩúcommunity-calls, maybe some community member will sent you some (as they have NO VALUE, you can also sent them to anyone and mint new ones)

Please keep this channel clean for builders, feedback and bugs, thanks
Also see the pinned messages first

Author: janek26
Content:
Hey all, we're aware of 2 major issues atm, and working to fix those! Due to christmas and new year I'd ask you for some more patience, we're working as fast as we can!

Main issues right now:
1. **Deployment**: It seems like the deployment of wallets is stuck. This is due to how we refresh the data. A wallets deployment status only gets updated if that wallet is selected (you can see the token balances of that wallet) **and** after you waited for >60 seconds. We're currently working to put all transaction tracking into the background process making this much more reliable.
2. **Password issue**: It seems like a few of you get stuck when entering the correct password. While the concrete issue here is still unknown, it's most likely that it's some messed up internal state. For now you should try to reset your extension and try to create a new wallet with a new password (dont use the backup file)

Author: petepetepete#9742
Content: What is the expected interaction between someone's L1 ethereum address and usage of the Argent wallet? I'm still wrapping my head around account management on starkware given everything is a contract. It seems like someone would in theory be able to bring their keypair from l1, but they'd still have a different l2 contract address, so would argent be able to pair with an L1 address if someone tried to bring it?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Yes, calling get_signer on the account contract will return the pubkey that is currently set as the signer on the contract. But in theory there is no guarantee that this key will still be valid when you use it to verify a signature. The correct way to verify that a signature is valid for the account is to call is_valid_signature on the account contract.

Author: wraitii
Content: right, and that takes [message hash, r, s] as arguments ?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: That‚Äôs correct, but r and s are passed as an array, so the arguments are (message hash, [r,s]).

Author: mottyl
Content:
Grt!
can you pls clarify the difference between support for "transaction queueing" and "supporting pending tx", if any?

Author: janek26
Content: there is a big difference

Author: janek26
Content: main feature of this release is that pending transactions get shown to the user. Additionally the extension now tracks the wallet nonce aswell locally and doesnt rely on chain data, this allows to have multiple pending transactions at the same time, with increasing nonces, which will all end up in a single block.

Author: janek26
Content: In the future this wont be used that often when batch transactions is implemented, but it‚Äôll still be a useful feature and it‚Äôs very useful right now

Author: mottyl
Content: tx! that's a very good clarification. so pending txs are actually not queued but rather sent in parallel to the sequencer with and incremental nonce. That's great!

Author: janek26
Content: ah yeah, sorry for the incorrect commit message

Author: mottyl
Content: Next week Starkware are going to launch v7 for SN - with support for "complex" txs. i.e.: users will be able to send `approve` + `swap` in a single tx

Author: mottyl
Content: can you share your plans for supporting that on the wallet side?

Author: janek26
Content: in practice this means you dont need to wait for the approval anymore on myswap, but can request 2 transactions to argent x, just make sure they get accepted by the sequencer (promise not throwing)

Author: mottyl
Content: but the user will still need to sign twice, right?

Author: mottyl
Content: (in the current case)

Author: janek26
Content: yep, we‚Äôll work on this asap. First the wallet contracts need to be updated, dont know if open zeppelin has defined a standard yet. After the contracts support this we‚Äôll tackle the ui asap

Author: martriay
Content: I‚Äôm currently trying to organize a few upcoming features into v0.1.0, the first release of the library. This currently DOES NOT include that feature yet and will probably prioritize other changes to accounts such as validation/execution steps for fee payments. Taking this into account (pun intended :p), it‚Äôs unlikely this feature gets released in January

Author: martriay
Content: But now that you let me know about your need, I‚Äôll try to prioritize it

Author: janek26
Content: I think integrating batch transactions asap should be top priority on that list tbh. As it‚Äòll change the account contract interface and ABI. If you dont include this every contract/dapp integrating with that version would need to adopt those changed once released.

Author: martriay
Content:
well 0.1.0 is not only about accounts, and for accounts the top priority is supporting the fee mechanism, then comes multicall. so i'd say it's quite prioritized.

on top of that, many changes to the abi are to be expected during these early development phases, I wouldn't worry too much about changing interfaces. without going further, each new contract needs to be whitelisted so there's not many systems that can deploy and integrate with this.

Author: martriay
Content: that being said, i'd love to accelerate the development of the lib: friendly reminder that we're hiring ^^

Author: mottyl

@Janek | argent.xyz the problem is not only with 2 tabs (which I agree it is a less interesting case), but rather when the user goes from one app to the other. E.g.: minting TST on argentlabs and then going to mySwap to swap tokens - starknet.signer.invokeFunction() never returns.

Content: Another example is Approve and Swap within mySwap - it makes it hard to have a consistent behavior and a good UX when we sometimes know that the user interact with the wallet (`sign` / `reject`) and other times we don't know...

Content:
Hi All!

I am working on a starknet project where most user interaction happens through a chrome extension that injects content scripts onto a web page.

I'd like to leverage argent-x for the starknet.js instance and providers it injects and avoid replicating all of that to interact with starknet. However, this is not possible right now due to the browser sandboxing everything injected by chrome extensions so there is no direct communication with argent-x. 

I found that metamask had the same issue in the past and it seems to have a ?simple? solution. I was wondering if this can be done for argent-x?

If this is something that can't be prioritized I'd be happy to look into it myself!

Thanks! 

Metamask Issue: https://github.com/MetaMask/metamask-extension/issues/940
Enhancement: https://github.com/MetaMask/metamask-extension/compare/v4.6.0...jakubsta:master

Author: peteris.
Content: what is the `get_signer` value on the ArgentX deployed contracts? trying to make ArgentX wallet the owner of a deployed contract and wondering if I should pass in the `get_signer()` value or the decimal value of the contract address?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: `get_signer`  will return the (public) key that is authorised to sign transactions and trigger actions on the account contract associated to an Argent X wallet. You can see it as the owner of the account. If you want to make an Argent X wallet the owner of another contract then you should pass the address of the account contract.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
The new version of Argent X (v2.1.0) has been released!

Main features:
- Ability to connect to a local network
- Support connection from multiple tabs
- Replace state machine by React router

Author: fredozz#8225
Content: hello friends, noob question there :  I see ArgentX is deploying it's own contract on the starknet chain, question is does it need to pay gas for it ?  if yes then how does a new user can pay if he/she has no wallet yet ?  if no then is there any risk of flooding the chain in case a malicious actor ( or a bug ) start to deploy x contracts per second ?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
That's a great question and the answer depends on how Starkware will implement fees in StarkNet. Fees are not yet implemented. Note also that your questions applies to all wallets since StarkNet implements account abstraction (i.e. all accounts are contracts), so it is not only related to Argent X. 

One possible solution is to use CREATE2 which means that you can know the address of a contract before deploying it. So you can imagine the user counterfactually creating an account (in practice only determining the future address). But from the UX point of view it is as if the account is created. Before doing an action with that account (e.g. minting an NFT) the user needs to fund it. Once the account is funded you can now deploy the contract and pay the fees which can be bundled with the first action.

Author: 9atetris
Content:
from one of JP users, questions about ArgentX,
> StarkNet alpha updated recently, is it safe to assume that the data in the wallet will not be lost due to future updates?
> 
> and can the same be said for wallets that were in use before the update?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
The next versions of StarkNet will require breaking changes to wallets to e.g. support fees. Remember that accounts in StarkNet are smart-contracts with fixed logic (for now). So while the data of your accounts may not be lost, they might not be supported by StarkNet and/or Argent X.

The good news is that the next version of StarkNet will enable us to deploy upgradable accounts. So the Argent X wallets that you will create in a couple of weeks will persist and evolve with StarkNet.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
The json file is a keystore which means it is your private key encrypted with your password. So when you restore your accounts with the json file you need to provide your password to decrypt it. We know that it is not the perfect experience but we are still in alpha. You have to be patient, we will get there.

I'm sorry to hear that you have the impression we are not responding to your message fast enough, but that's because the entire team is working hard on improving the product. More time on discord means less building... and we are trying to find the right balance. 

We are growing the team so it will improve on all fronts, including support.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
For the moment the plan is to have 1 keypair per account which gives you more privacy (you cannot link the accounts because they use the same signer). But in the end you control the account contract and you can change the signer. So you could set the same signer on all your accounts if you want. This is not yet exposed in the front-end, but it is supported by the account contract.

With the next release of Argent X (later today) the account will become a proxy delegating to an implementation. You could imagine having different implementations for different accounts.

Author: cecco_
Content: What's the recommended way to upgrade to v3 while supporting v2 wallets?

Author: cecco_
Content: From the code it looks like `Contract.invoke` accepts the invocation signature as the last element of `args`, so if I use the old `starknet.signer`to sign the call it should work?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Chrome should auto-update the extension once released on the store (currently under review) so there should be no v2 wallet to interact with your v3 dapp

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: we did try to be backward compatible to give time for dapps to upgrade, but only the legacy signer is supported.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: the provider will be v3 so dapps using the provider should update rapidly

Author: cecco_
Content: So now I'm working around by checking if the `starknet` object has the new account or the old signer. In case they have the old signer I don't invoke contracts directly, but use the `Contract.populateTransaction` and then `addTransaction`.

Author: cecco_
Content: But then I have some issues with `Contract.call` because it's connected to the old provider üôÇ

Author: cecco_
Content: So I think it's better if I split the provider from the account to avoid issues in the future.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: the problem I think is that the old signer will always be there; it's there in v2 wallet and we inject it as well with v3 wallet to be backward compatible with v2 dapps

Author: cecco_
Content: I think it's fine, I first check for account and only if it fails fall back to the old signer.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: alternatively you could check the version in the `starknet`. object

Author: nelzone#4776
Content:
hello Argent X team! - i'm in the process of implementing ERC-20 token approvals for a dapp i'm building and a few questions came up during this process:


1. is there a minimum  allowance  required  for a given token to be considered "approved" (i.e. allow smart contract to spend token balance)? 

2. if no allowance is specified, does the spender permission amount default to anything? 

3. what's the max allowance amount for a starknet wallet? Metamask's concept of "infinite" is 1.157920892373162e+59

4. if my dapp requests the "infinite" amount for spend allowance, will users have the ability to modify this permission in the Argent X UI? (question likely more for Argent X team)

Author: coldlight8626
Content: hey guys,How to use privatekey import Argent X?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Thanks, we will have a look.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: For the moment yes.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
1. There is no minimum allowance, the spender will only be allowed to take whatever amount has been approved.
2. The default allowance is 0
3. In Cairo the max allowance is probably the maximum number that fits in a `felt` 
4. That's a great feature and it will definitely be in Argent X at some point, but it's not the case currently

This being said, infinite approvals is a terrible idea from a security point of view (you're basically allowing the spender to take all your tokens... and the spender may well be a proxy with a different implementation in the future). At Argent we've been pushing the ecosystem to move away from it for years.

The great news is that StarkNet supports multicalls by default, so in a single transaction you can `approve` and `call` . If your dapp needs to take `X` tokens, you can do a multicall that approves `X` then call your dapp in a single transaction.

Author: _dsi
Content: I think it's the offset between the `callArray` and `calldata` of a function call, if someone has confirmation I would appreciate üòÑ

Author: andra0345
Content: oh.thank u üòç

Author: janek26
Content: maybe @martriay can help

Author: martriay
Content:
sup! it's the size of each call's calldata. since Cairo doesn't yet support struct arrays with pointers on external functions, we make up for it by faking the structs and manually reconstructing them from the intermediate representation called `AccountCallArray`, which keeps two arrays: one for `to`, `selector`, and `calldata_len` of each call, and another one for all of the `calldata`. the  `data_offset` variable is the size of each call's calldata used to traverse that array in this function:

https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/main/src/openzeppelin/account/library.cairo#L214-L236

Author: peteris.
Content: Argent X 3 works really well with Voyager, but Argent X 2 doesn't seem to work for me so I'm not able to transfer ownership from the Argent X 2 contract to the Argent X 3 contract. (I can still do token transfers from 2->3 via the wallet but not Voyager transactions). Is that expected?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
Ha I see, I thought the 2 and 3 where typos for X üôÇ

Voyager (and Argent X v3) is using the latest version of `starknet.js`. while Argent X v2 is using an older version with a breaking change in the Provider. 

I think some people tried 2 approaches to transfer (non ERC20) assets from Argent X v2 to v3. One is to extract the signer of your accounts and transfer the assets with a script. But I don't know if they succeeded. The other option is to use Argent X v2 with an older version of Voyager. Maybe @Henri-l | StarkWare will know more about these 2 options.

Author: janek26
Content:
**I'm very happy to announce a new Argent X version has released! **

Argent X v3.2.0  will enable you to view your Account history with friendly support from @Voyager team !
We also switched from backup files to seed phrases to provide a more common backup method, which you can still use when you forget your password. As you all know we at Argent are no huge fans of Seed Phrases, and therefore we're already working on an smart contract wallet alternative, maybe you can already spot something üôÇ 
Additionally you can now add/edit/remove custom networks as a last minute feature, which got requested by the StarkWare team in the context of the Hackaton!

Full release notes can be found here: https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-x/releases/tag/v3.2.0

See you in Amsterdam!

Author: _dsi
Content:
Hey guys, I found something weird and figured out it was the best chan to search answers. I found a weird call array 
```
[
  '0xc3511006c04ef1d78af4c8e0e74ec18a6e64ff9e',
  '0x1054de4ceecb941b320665951d8b932184bb07a5f66277205b179cea1692e79',
  '0x16345785d8a0000',
  '0x0'
]
```
Usually call arrays are structured this way
```
[
  '0x2', // call array length
  '0x7394cbe418daa16e42b87ba67372d4ab4a5df0b05c6e554d158458ce245bc10', // to
  '0x219209e083275171774dab1df80982e9df2096516f06319c5c6d71ae0a8480c', // selector
  '0x0', // data offset
  '0x3', // data len
  '0x71faa7d6c3ddb081395574c5a6904f4458ff648b66e2123b877555d9ae0260e', // ...
  '0x15543c3708653cda9d418b4ccd3be11368e40636c10c44b18cfe756b6d88b29',
  '0x3',
  '0x6',
  '0x9',
  '0x71faa7d6c3ddb081395574c5a6904f4458ff648b66e2123b877555d9ae0260e',
  '0x3635c9adc5dea00000',
  '0x0',
  '0x4',
  '0x7394cbe418daa16e42b87ba67372d4ab4a5df0b05c6e554d158458ce245bc10',
  '0x3635c9adc5dea00000',
  '0x0',
  '0x2c0083574d8',
  '0x0',
  '0x13'
]
```
but as you can see in the first array, the call array length appears to be 0xc3511006c04ef1d78af4c8e0e74ec18a6e64ff9e which is an extremely large number, and is just wrong rn
Any idea how this first call array is structured ?
I'm trying to understand it but of course I get an error when trying to decode is with the default tool when trying to convert calldata[0] into a number (too large) to get the call array length

Author: hypnosh0ck
Content:
Hi there team Argent.  I'm trying to sign a message in node.js using an account I've deployd via the ArgentX plugin. I feel like I'm really close to getting it working but I can't seem to get the keys that correspond to my first argent account. How do I do this? I've tried the following:

I extracted my private key from the keystore using ethers `pk = await Wallet.fromEncryptedJson(backupFileJSON, password)` and then generated the key pair using `ec.getKeyPair(pk)` from the starknet.js lib
unfortunately the public key doesn't match the one that I see if I call `get_signer()` on my account contract.

I then tried using the mnemonic and using ethers `Wallet.fromMnemonic` to get at the signer. This gives me the same key pair as above.

I thought that perhaps to get at my first set of Argent account keys I'd need to use the derivationPath specified in the argent backup file

`Wallet.fromMnemonic(selectedNetwork.l2.mnemonic, "m/2645'/1195502025'/1148870696'/0'/0'/0");`

This yields a different key pair but not the one that matches my first argent account.
Feels like I'm missing one tiny thing but I'm not sure what I need to do. I thought that maybe I was using an incorrect EC but I'm using `ec` from starknet.js so that should be the right curve?

Author: .tom138
Content:
Hi all, I'm not sure if it was already mentioned or not, may it is helpful. So I have figured out that, if you try to make a transaction on xbank for example and the gas fee is not fully calculated in the argent wallet, it is still possible to sign the transaction, but it will not be sent. But if you repeat the process and wait for the gas fee price accordingly, then the transaction is sent.

It would be good if it could be considered that that signing is only possible when the gas fee is finally calculated. As it is with MetaMask, there it is only possible to confirm a transaction if the gas fee is calculated.  Please let me know your thoughts.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: That's because StarkNet uses account abstraction which means that every account is a smart-contract that needs to be deployed. The drawback is that each account has a different address, but there are tons of benefits with that approach such as native multicalls, social recovery, etc.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Events such as which page is opened, which button is clicked, etc. But with nothing related to who did the action (no user ID, no account address, no transaction hash, etc).  Just a plain "this button was clicked / this page was opened".

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: No, for now Argent X is only for StarkNet.

Author: gregoryguillou
Content:
Hello, I'm facing an issue with one of my accounts of an argent-x instance on goerli. You might be interested to dig into it as my other accounts work fine. I was expected the nonce to be managed by the account contract only but hey, I'm obviously wrong.

No bid deal for me. I can simply wipe out the wallet. I'm yet curious to know if there is a way to resync the nonce.

Below the details:
tx: 0x64ec54396212c10a031a7ddf681ac0e64bcaab0c43d4a3a8a0ccc4b3d6d46eb
command: starknet get_transaction --hash $tx
error message:
```
Error at pc=0:12:
Got an exception while executing a hint.
Cairo traceback (most recent call last):
Unknown location (pc=0:140)
Unknown location (pc=0:126)

Error in the called contract (0x5602e12b9bfa995f66206995e1cfe6cd0763c0a017821f62d4c82e0d73e5e20):
Error message: nonce invalid
Error at pc=0:1624:
An ASSERT_EQ instruction failed: 1 != 5.
Cairo traceback (most recent call last):
Unknown location (pc=0:844)
Unknown location (pc=0:697)
```

I love argent-x and your work btw! I'm looking forward for the mobile version üöÄ. Thank you for your energy.

Author: 0xrya
Content: @Julien | argent.xyz can u guys add private key imports?

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
This is not currently planned and harder than it may seem. 

Remember that on StarkNet we have account abstraction so a private key is not directly linked to an account (which is a contract). So importing a key alone will not do much; you would need to import a key and the account associated.

But we are working on a standard to make these kind of things easier on StarkNet https://community.starknet.io/t/account-keys-and-addresses-derivation-standard/1230

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
Don't worry, you will never loose the funds you've bridged to mainnet.

StarkNet released v0.9 with braking changes on testnet. So you only need to create new accounts and migrate your assets on testnet. 

But the same change will be applied to mainnet in ~2 weeks. At that point you will need to create a new mainnet account and transfer your 0.25 ETH. But we will always make it easy to migrate your funds from the old account to the new one.

Author: seallywaghook

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
Unfortunately there is nothing we can do. StarkNet introduced braking changes and your current account will stop working at some point in the near future. So you need to create a new account and transfer your assets.

Remember that StarkNet is still in alpha so braking changes are to be expected. But the network is maturing and hopefully this is the last one.

Author: uPebe#9637
Content:
Hello everybody. Have a couple of questions:

1) Is it possible to recover old `deleted` accounts? 
(Thought it was only going to hide them but instead they are gone. Couldn't find a way to recover them even after recovering the wallet, etc). 

2) Also, in the `voyager` isn't it possible to see the incoming transactions? (e.g.: If I send ETH from addressA to addressB. This transaction doesn't show up in addressB, so addressB doesn't know where the funds come from).

Thanks in advance.

Author: 0xrya
Content: can we expect private key + account import soons? i dont wanna delete my accounts everytime there is an update :kek:

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content:
1/ Unfortunately not with the current version but we have a PR to fix that. So if you deleted your old accounts today they are gone. But when the same change applies to mainnet in ~2 weeks accounts will be hidden and recoverables.

2/ It depends on the token but the current version of ETH on StarkNet does not emit a Transfer event so impossible to detect when ETH has been received. This should change in the near future.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: This should be the last braking change affecting proxies so all following changes of the network should be manageable with an upgrade of the implementation. Remember that we've designed Argent X accounts to be proxies that can be upgraded. So from now on you should be able to keep your addresses even if the network does a braking change.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Technically you should be able to transfer them in batch since the Argent X account supports multicalls but we did not build a UI for that yet üôÇ

Author: uPebe#9637
Content: Ok, thanks @Julien | argent.xyz for the quick response üëç

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Since the update to 0.9 on Monday the Goerli testnet has been experiencing issues. You should always check the top right corner: if you see a warning sign it means the network is struggling.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Please make sure you have some ETH on your account. StarkNet just introduced mandatory fees on testnet so you must pay for your transactions.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: Are you sure you are on 4.0.1? I had the same problem yesterday with 4.0.0 but it worked for me with 4.0.1.

Author: julien.argent.xyz
Content: It should be the last time this happens but unfortunately StarkNet is in alpha and may introduce braking changes from time to time. However the network is rapidly maturing thanks to all the testing you guys are doing üôÇ

Author: tuya#9656
Content:
**Q1: What is the difference between Argent X and Argent mobile APP?**
Argent X is a wallet deployed on StarkNet
Argent mobile APP is a wallet deployed on the Ethereum mainnet and zkSync.

**Q2: Can the mnemonic of MetaMask be used to create an Argent X wallet?**
While possible, we discourage it. 
You should try to keep different wallets separate and secure. So we recommend you to create a new Argent X wallet

**Q3: Can the addresses of Argent X and MetaMask be transferred to each other?**
No they can't. Accounts on StarkNet are smart-contracts so their address is computed differently then on Ethereum. If you send funds to a MetaMask address on StarkNet your funds will be lost.

**Q4: Where to get eth faucet?**
L1 goerli for Ethereum
https://goerlifaucet.com/
https://faucets.chain.link/goerli
L2 goerli for StarkNet
https://faucet.goerli.starknet.io/#
if L2 cant work, you can also use starkgate to transfer L1 eth to L2.
https://goerli.starkgate.starknet.io/

**Q5,: where can I find the installation package of the previous version of Argent X?**
https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-x/releases

Author: hos5ein
Content:
Argent X is a wallet deployed on StarkNet
Argent mobile APP is a wallet deployed on the Ethereum mainnet and zkSync.
If you are going to donate with Argent, click the Wallet connect option and connect to Argent this way.  After connecting the wallet, click on the Proceed option to move to a new page. Do not close this page in any way until the payment process is complete.  In the new page that you transferred, first connect the wallet and then click on the Complete payment button.  After completing the payment process, on the gitcoin page, you should see the message You've successfully contributed, which means the completion of the donating process.

Author: tuya#9656
Content:
FAQ from Argent community
---------------------------------
**Q1. Wallet is not deployed: **
it will be fixed in 4.1.2 in several hours.

**Q2. Can't migrate funds: **
Also will be resolved in 4.1.2

**Q3. Will I lose my starknet mainnet funds? **
No.

**Q4. Will I lose my transaction history?**
Yes, as you will need to use a new wallet

**Q5. Why is it happening?**
StarkNet mainnet has gotten an update that will make old contracts (and therefore wallets) obsolete, it is a good thing as it means StarkNet is developing.

**Q6. Is there a deadline for the migration?**
Migration will be available for a couple weeks at least, please stay tuned for more accurate deadline.

**Q7. I have no ETH, only other assets in mainnet wallet: **
You will need to deposit some ETH through Starkgate or from another starknet wallet to your old address to send assets.

Author: tuya#9656
Content:
The previous old address may be like this, because the old address will be deprecated in the future. Therefore, some projects allow users to submit test records after testing and give them roles. rather than by address.
For newly deployed wallets, the mainnet address and testnet address are the same, hopefully they won't change again.

Author: tuya#9656
Content:
1. Follow the prompts to deploy your new wallet and copy its address
2. Send the token of the old wallet to the newly deployed wallet.   each migration requires eth as a fee, about 0.0003

Author: ismael_eth
Content:
üì£üì£ Argent X v4.4.1 now availableüì£üì£
@here

We're super excited for our latest release. It includes 2 huge improvements in UX: Fiat values and Transaction review with risk assessment.

Fiat values: Now on Argent X, when on Mainnet, you can see the equivalent value in dollars.

Transaction review and Risk assessment: Right before signing a transaction, you'll get comprehensive details about what it's actually doing. 
For certain transactions, Argent X will display a message with a risk assessment message, letting the user know about potential scams and also verified transactions trusted by Argent. 


Learn more about it and our future announcements on twitter:
https://twitter.com/argentHQ/status/1549380860524302339?s=20&t=b5KKAzBYFqiqnhEbQ58ByQ

To get the update, make sure to restart your browser in the coming hours.

Content:
üì£üì£ Argent X v4.6.1 now availableüì£üì£
@here

We're including two big UX improvements: 

- Let Dapps access individual accounts:
Now when connecting to a Dapp, you'll be able to select which account it has access to. No way to link your accounts together without your permission.
- Hide and unhide accounts:
If you have many accounts you can now choose which ones to show

Learn more about it and our future announcements on twitter:

To get the update, make sure to restart your browser in the coming hours.

Content: As you know, the old address will be deprecated, so you need to transfer funds from the old address to the new address

2. Send the token of the old wallet to the newly deployed wallet. each migration requires eth as gas

Author: karakasfrd
scarletssstarktitan
Content:
Sorry for your inconvenience, recently StarkNet's a bit backlogged due to heavy load, so it happens. For details you can check the docs below.
https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/develop/Blocks/transaction-life-cycle/
Methods you can try when it comes to Rejected:
1. Check if your StarkNet wallet(Argent x or Braavos) is upgraded to the latest version.
2. Restart your browser and keep trying. If it's a withdrawal or transfer on StarkNet, pls check if your wallet has sufficient balance, or pls try a small withdraw first, and you can increase (edit) gas fee on the review page (Currently seems only available on Braavos wallet). 
3. If you have VPN enabled, try switching to another node; If you are using VPS, pls try on other computers 
Finally, it'd be so helpful if you can share the Rejected tx for us to investigate, thank you very much!
would you like to rule out this possibility ,and try again ser

Author: wind.rider
Content:
ser,just link closer said,pls rejoin again:
Also here are two solutions from the argent x community about this issue, pls check it:
On issues during the upgrade. 
Issue 1.
If you are seeing an error Error message: implementation invalid - you are trying to upgrade a deprecated wallet. You will need to create a new one. 
You can use our CLI tool to send the assets from the old wallet to the new one. If you are using mac, there is a video with the steps from our developers: https://www.loom.com/share/668e72c4729d4da5b46841383cf569c6
and here you can find a guide for Windows: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Fs-X7xjHsb7yD2jZB8qkHCeteClufjHd/view?usp=sharing
You can't keep the old address as it was never upgraded and is now deprecated, but using the instruction above you can move the assets you have in the wallet.
Note: If the CLI tool is crashing, please DM me when it does so, we are looking into this. 

Issue 2. 
If you are seeing 
```Error message: Proxy: caller is not admin
Error at pc=0:302:
An ASSERT_EQ instruction failed: 0 !=  ```

This means that you likely recovered your Argent wallet in another StarkNet wallet (e.g. Braavos), and this would have changed the contract. We are working on a fix and thank you for your patience. In the meantime, a workaround would be to either use that other wallet, or create a new Argent wallet and send the assets from the old one to the new address. If you can't use the wallet in another extension, please reach out to their support team for help. 

thank you

Author: scarletssstarktitan
Content:
If you are seeing an error Error message: implementation invalid - you are trying to upgrade a deprecated wallet. You will need to create a new one. 
You can use our CLI tool to send the assets from the old wallet to the new one. If you are using mac, there is a video with the steps from our developers: https://www.loom.com/share/668e72c4729d4da5b46841383cf569c6
and here you can find a guide for Windows: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Fs-X7xjHsb7yD2jZB8qkHCeteClufjHd/view?usp=sharing
You can't keep the old address as it was never upgraded and is now deprecated, but using the instruction above you can move the assets you have in the wallet.
Note: If the CLI tool is crashing, please  Best to email support@argent.xyz

Author: wind.rider
Content:
ser,pls check out the argent x team's reply to this issue:
> Issue 1.
> If you are seeing an error `Error message: implementation invalid `- you are trying to upgrade a deprecated wallet. You will need to create a new one. 
> You can use our CLI tool to send the assets from the old wallet to the new one. If you are using mac, there is a video with the steps from our developers: https://www.loom.com/share/668e72c4729d4da5b46841383cf569c6
> and here you can find a guide for Windows: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Fs-X7xjHsb7yD2jZB8qkHCeteClufjHd/view?usp=sharing
> You can't keep the old address as it was never upgraded and is now deprecated, but using the instruction above you can move the assets you have in the wallet.
> Note: If the CLI tool is crashing, please DM me when it does so, we are looking into this.
If you need further consultation, pls join the argent x community and get support on the argent x support channel:https://discord.com/invite/GWSyrHg , thank youüòÄ

Content:
ser,pls check this reply from the argent x team:
> If you are seeing an error Error message: **implementation invalid - you are trying to upgrade a deprecated wallet. You will need to create a new one. **
> You can use our CLI tool to send the assets from the old wallet to the new one. You can find a guide here: https://support.argent.xyz/hc/en-us/articles/8846173853341-Using-CLI-tool-to-recover-assets You can't keep the old address as it was never upgraded and is now deprecated, but using the instruction above you can move the assets you have in the wallet.
> Please make sure to use the latest CLI tool: https://github.com/argentlabs/argent-starknet-recover/releases/tag/v0.4.2

Author: protoplanetary
Content: Hi, any idea what's up with this error in ArgentX on Goerli Starknet? It happens after I submit the tx and Starknet rejects it; ArgentX does not predict any errors. I have no control over the gas that ArgentX selects.

Author: protoplanetary
Content: `Actual fee exceeded max fee.`

Author: protoplanetary
Content:
I see this answer from previously 

> it shows actual fee exceeded max fee,we are aware that the fee transfer failure occurs during a spike in gas price and the max fee < actual fee, argent x doesn't allow you to set your own max fee at this time, you can keep trying and it should eventually work,thank you

so I suppose it's an ArgentX bug then? Either keep better track of what Starknet is charging for gas, or let us set our own max fee?

Author: protoplanetary
Content: As a side note, after it happens all subsequent transactions' nonces are off by one, and fail. ArgentX should detect transaction failures that don't increment the nonce, and cancel subsequent queued transactions and request they be signed again with the correct nonce.

Author: wind.rider
Content: or pls try again for another time period, ser, usually when we encounter a rejected status showing actual fee exceeded max fee, we would recommend a few more tries and it'll work, also if you have any suggestions for argent x wallet, feel free to join their community: https://discord.gg/T4PDFHxm6T, thank youüòÄ

Content: Hello, is it possible to restore access to the wallet through a private key?

Author: wind.rider
Content:
Ser,pls check this reply from argent x team,thank you:
Unfortunately, we will not implement the private key option in order to recover your account, I'm afraid. Only seed phrase or social recovery methods are currently in development.

Our developers built a CLI tool on transferring the assets. You can't recover the wallet via private key, you can only recover the funds in it and send them to a new address.

You can find a guide here: https://support.argent.xyz/hc/en-us/articles/8846173853341-Using-CLI-tool-to-recover-assets

You can find a guide here: https://support.argent.xyz/hc/en-us/articles/8846173853341-Using-CLI-tool-to-recover-assets You can't keep the old address as it was never upgraded and is now deprecated, but using the instruction above you can move the assets you have in the wallet.

Author: rektor
Content: hi! what could be the consequences of transferring a seed phrase from a Metamask to an Argent?

Author: wind.rider
Content: Ser, starknet supports account abstraction, so the addresses are CA(not EOA like metamask address in ethereum),so if you use the metamask seed phrase in argent x, you can only generate a new starknet account, but not recover the metamask account,fyi,thank you

Content: ser, code 32000 happened recently in the new version of mm wallet, AFAIK it happens not only in L1 ethereum mainnet but also in other sidechains like polygon, when some users switch to another browser or rpc, the problem can be solved, please try the above method, if it still appears, please check this support document from metamask: https://support.metamask.io/hc/en-us/articles/4402538041869-Error-ethjs-query-while-formatting-outputs-from-RPC-transaction-underpriced-error- ,or pls check if there is a transaction with a pending status in your mm wallet, if so, pls handle this transaction first: https://support.metamask.io/hc/en-us/articles/360015489251-How-to-speed-up-or-cancel-a-pending-transaction ,thank you

Author: mandip_
Content:
I believe the first error is due to pending deposit, which has been pending since 3 days. First please either speed up or cancel pending deposit transaction following guidelines here https://support.metamask.io/hc/en-us/articles/360015489251-How-to-speed-up-or-cancel-a-pending-transaction

The gwei of pending deposit is 7 gwei, which is less than the current base gwei (keeps on changing), please increase your gwei to more than current base gwei as well as priority gwei accordingly, and speed up transaction

The second option can be cancelling the transaction. The nonce of your pending deposit is 37

Content:
You can use :
Canceling a transaction - Method 2: Custom nonce. Nonce of your transaction is 37. Please follow the guidelines provided above of method 2. If this does not solve, reach out to metamask support at thttps://support.metamask.io/ and click Start a Conversation
Once you click Start a Conversation a live chat bot will appear on your screen. It will give you an automated response at first, but afterwards you should be able to contact the support team directly

Author: thegentlleman
Content:
Can you ask me. Starknet is a EVM blockchain?
And does my MetaMask and ArgentX/Braavos linked if I will use bridge

Author: scarletssstarktitan
Content:
i am not sure i understand your question correctly , 
1st , starknet is not EVM blockchain , it is a Validity Rollup Layer 2. It provides high throughput, low gas costs, and retains Ethereum Layer 1 levels of security
2nd , if you try to bridge your fund between two different chain , like between starknet ( AKA L2 network ) and other chain ( L1 ethereum or other L2 network ) you should connect with the metamask ( support evm chain ) and argent x /braavos ( support starknet ) via the bridge thank u

```
pl: Error at pc=0:15647: Got an exception while executing a hint. Cairo traceback (most recent call last): Unknown location (pc=0:233) Unknown location (pc=0:5191) Unknown location (pc=0:11307) Error in the called contract (0x41a78e741e5af2fec34b695679bc6891742439f7afb8484ecd7766661ad02bf): Error at pc=0:32: Got an exception while executing a hint.
